'''Frank Allen Sloan''' (born August 15, 1942) is an [[United States|American]] health economist. In 2015 he is the J. Alexander McMahon Professor of Health Policy and Management and Professor of Economics at [[Duke University]].<ref>[http://www.medpagetoday.com/Ophthalmology/GeneralOphthalmology/34188 "New Study Shows No Vitamin D Link to Macular Degeneration"]. ''MedPage Today'',  Crystal Phend</ref><ref name="MehlmanNance">{{cite book|author1=Maxwell J. Mehlman|author2=Dale A. Nance|title=The Case Against "Health Courts"|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0dCTStWJlyoC&pg=PA53|publisher=AAJ|pages=53–|id=GGKEY:H2W17LJFF0Z}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Sloan was born in the [[United States]] and received his A.B. in Economics from [[Oberlin College]] in 1964 and his Ph.D in Economics from [[Harvard University]] in 1969.  His dissertation was on the Economic Models of Physician Supply.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}

==Career==

After graduation, Sloan worked as a research economist at the [[RAND Corporation]].
Sloan served as the Centennial Professor of Economics at [[Vanderbilt University]] from April 1984 to June 1993. Sloan was appointed as the J. Alexander McMahon Professor of Health Policy and Management and Professor of Economics at [[Duke University]] in 1993. He also served as director of the Duke Center for [[Health Policy]], Law and Management from 1998 to 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Duke Economics|url=http://econ.duke.edu/people?Gurl=/aas/Economics&Uil=fsloan&subpage=profile|website=duke.edu|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref>

Sloan researches and writes about the [[economic]] aspects of health issues.<ref name="Cimasi2005">{{cite book|author=Robert James Cimasi|title=The U.S. Healthcare Certificate of Need Sourcebook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nh8eSdNFB8MC&pg=PA14|year=2005|publisher=Beard Books|isbn=978-1-58798-275-0|pages=14–}}</ref><ref>[http://www.webmd.com/diabetes/news/20080128/diabetes-rates-rise-in-older-population "Diabetes Rates Rise in Older Population"]. By Jennifer Warner, ''WebMD Health News'', Reviewed by Louise Chang, MD</ref><ref name="Daniels1998">{{cite book|author=Mark Ross Daniels|title=Medicaid Reform and the American States: Case Studies on the Politics of Managed Care|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w8l8kQ9Xp44C&pg=PA69|date=1 January 1998|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-86569-263-3|pages=69–}}</ref> He is the author of a number of books detailing the results of his investigations. He has also written or contributed to more than 300 published articles on a variety of [[medical]] topics, ranging from macular degeneration<ref>[http://www.todaysgeriatricmedicine.com/news/ex_041514.shtml "Anti-VEGF Treats Wet Macular Degeneration"]. ''Today's Geriatric Medicine'', By Jennifer Anderson</ref> to government economic policy.<ref name="Palmer1982">{{cite book|author=John Logan Palmer|title=The Reagan Experiment: An Examination of Economic and Social Policies Under the Reagan Administration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=clik4pH4vGQC&pg=PA512|year=1982|publisher=The Urban Institute|isbn=978-0-87766-315-7|pages=512–}}</ref>

