The '''NRL Judiciary''' is the disciplinary [[judiciary]] of the [[National Rugby League]] (NRL), a [[rugby league]] competition. The Judiciary regulates the conduct of players, [[Rugby league match officials|referees]], and [[Rugby league match officials|other officials]] associated with the NRL and its clubs.<ref>https://www.nrl.com/operations/the-game/judiciary-code/</ref><ref>https://www.nrl.com/news/topic/judiciary/</ref>
The NRL Judiciary is made up of former players who convene in three-man panels to rule on on-field incidents. The judiciary is currently chaired by [[Wollongong]] district court judge [[Paul Conlon]] and made up of former players [[Mal Cochrane]], [[Michael Buettner]], [[Bradley Clyde]], [[Sean Garlick]], [[Don McKinnon (rugby league)|Don McKinnon]] and [[Bob Lindner]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Dean Ritchie |author2=Christian Nicolussi |lastauthoramp=yes | title = Johnathan Thurston let-off backfires on NRL| work=The Daily Telegraph| place =Australia| publisher=[[Herald Sun|Herald and Weekly Times]].| date = 4 June 2010| url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/nrl/johnathan-thurston-let-off-backfires-on-nrl/story-e6frfgbo-1225875234968| accessdate =3 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Brent Read |author2=Stuart Honeysett |lastauthoramp=yes | title = The rule shift that saved Jarryd Hayne|work=The Australian| place =Australia| publisher=News Limited| date = 10 June 2010| url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/the-rule-shift-that-saved-jarryd-hayne/story-e6frg7mf-1225877656528| accessdate =9 June 2010}}</ref>
An integrity unit was formed on 7 February 2013 and is headed by former Federal Court judge Tony Whitlam.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/rugby-league/league-news/nrl-creates-integrity-unit-in-response-to-crime-commission-probe-into-australian-sport-20130207-2e02a.html |title=NRL creates integrity unit in response to Crime Commission probe into Australian sport |publisher=Smh.com.au |date=24 July 2012 |accessdate=1 July 2013}}</ref>
